class ApplicationWindow(Window, Gio.ActionGroup, Gio.ActionMap, Accessible, Buildable, ConstraintTarget, Native, Root, ShortcutManager):
    """
    A :class:`Gtk.Window` subclass that integrates with :class:`Gtk.Application`.

    Notably, :class:`Gtk.ApplicationWindow` can handle an application menubar.

    This class implements the :class:`Gio.ActionGroup` and :class:`Gio.ActionMap`
    interfaces, to let you add window-specific actions that will be exported
    by the associated :class:`Gtk.Application`, together with its application-wide
    actions. Window-specific actions are prefixed with the “win.”
    prefix and application-wide actions are prefixed with the “app.”
    prefix. Actions must be addressed with the prefixed name when
    referring to them from a menu model.

    Note that widgets that are placed inside a :class:`Gtk.ApplicationWindow`
    can also activate these actions, if they implement the
    :class:`Gtk.Actionable` interface.

    The settings :attr:`Gtk.Settings.gtk-shell-shows-app-menu` and
    :attr:`Gtk.Settings.gtk-shell-shows-menubar` tell GTK whether the
    desktop environment is showing the application menu and menubar
    models outside the application as part of the desktop shell.
    For instance, on OS X, both menus will be displayed remotely;
    on Windows neither will be.

    If the desktop environment does not display the menubar, it can be shown in
    the :class:`Gtk.ApplicationWindow` by setting the
    :attr:`Gtk.ApplicationWindow.show-menubar` property to true. If the
    desktop environment does not display the application menu, then it will
    automatically be included in the menubar or in the window’s client-side
    decorations.

    See :class:`Gtk.PopoverMenu` for information about the XML language
    used by :class:`Gtk.Builder` for menu models.

    See also: :meth:`Gtk.Application.set_menubar`.

    ## A :class:`Gtk.ApplicationWindow` with a menubar

    The code sample below shows how to set up a :class:`Gtk.ApplicationWindow`
    with a menu bar defined on the :class:`Gtk.Application`:

    .. code-block:: c

        :class:`Gtk.Application` *app = :meth:`Gtk.Application.new` ("org.gtk.test", 0);

        :class:`Gtk.Builder` *builder = :meth:`Gtk.Builder.new_from_string` (
            "<interface>"
            "  <menu id='menubar'>"
            "    <submenu>"
            "      <attribute name='label' translatable='yes'>_Edit</attribute>"
            "      <item>"
            "        <attribute name='label' translatable='yes'>_Copy</attribute>"
            "        <attribute name='action'>win.copy</attribute>"
            "      </item>"
            "      <item>"
            "        <attribute name='label' translatable='yes'>_Paste</attribute>"
            "        <attribute name='action'>win.paste</attribute>"
            "      </item>"
            "    </submenu>"
            "  </menu>"
            "</interface>",
            -1);

        GMenuModel *menubar = G_MENU_MODEL (:meth:`Gtk.Builder.get_object` (builder, "menubar"));
        :meth:`Gtk.Application.set_menubar` (GTK_APPLICATION (app), menubar);
        g_object_unref (builder);

