    When subclassing a widget that implements :class:`Gtk.CellLayout` like
    :class:`Gtk.IconView` or :class:`Gtk.ComboBox`, there are some considerations related
    to the fact that these widgets internally use a :class:`Gtk.CellArea`.
    The cell area is exposed as a construct-only property by these
    widgets. This means that it is possible to e.g. do

    .. code-block:: c

        GtkWIdget *combo =
          g_object_new (GTK_TYPE_COMBO_BOX, "cell-area", my_cell_area, NULL);

    to use a custom cell area with a combo box. But construct properties
    are only initialized after instance ``init()``
    functions have run, which means that using functions which rely on
    the existence of the cell area in your subclass ``init()`` function will
    cause the default cell area to be instantiated. In this case, a provided
    construct property value will be ignored (with a warning, to alert
    you to the problem).

    .. code-block:: c

        static void
        my_combo_box_init (MyComboBox *b)
        {
          :class:`Gtk.CellRenderer` *cell;

          cell = :meth:`Gtk.CellRendererPixbuf.new`;

          // The following call causes the default cell area for combo boxes,
          // a :class:`Gtk.CellAreaBox`, to be instantiated
          :meth:`Gtk.CellLayout.pack_start` (GTK_CELL_LAYOUT (b), cell, FALSE);
          ...
        }

        :class:`Gtk.Widget` *
        my_combo_box_new (:class:`Gtk.CellArea` *area)
