    is that you will embed a :class:`Gtk.Text` inside a complex widget, and want to
    delegate the editable functionality to that text widget. :class:`Gtk.Editable`
    provides some utility functions to make this easy.

    In your class_init function, call :func:`Gtk.Editable.install_properties`,
    passing the first available property ID:

    .. code-block:: c

        static void
        my_class_init (MyClass *class)
        {
          ...
          g_object_class_install_properties (object_class, NUM_PROPERTIES, props);
          :func:`Gtk.editable_install_properties` (object_clas, NUM_PROPERTIES);
          ...
        }

    In your interface_init function for the :class:`Gtk.Editable` interface, provide
    an implementation for the get_delegate vfunc that returns your text widget:

    .. code-block:: c

        :class:`Gtk.Editable` *
        get_editable_delegate (:class:`Gtk.Editable` *editable)
        {
          return GTK_EDITABLE (MY_WIDGET (editable)->text_widget);
        }

        static void
        my_editable_init (:class:`Gtk.EditableInterface` *iface)
        {
          iface->get_delegate = get_editable_delegate;
        }

    You don't need to provide any other vfuncs. The default implementations
    work by forwarding to the delegate that the :class:`Gtk.EditableInterface`.get_delegate()
    vfunc returns.

    In your instance_init function, create your text widget, and then call
    :meth:`Gtk.Editable.init_delegate`:

    .. code-block:: c

        static void
        my_widget_init (MyWidget *self)
        {
          ...
          self->text_widget = :meth:`Gtk.Text.new`;
          :meth:`Gtk.Editable.init_delegate` (GTK_EDITABLE (self));
          ...
        }

