class Expander(Widget, Accessible, Buildable, ConstraintTarget):
    """
    Allows the user to reveal or conceal a child widget.

    <picture>
      <source srcset="expander-dark.png" media="(prefers-color-scheme: dark)">
      <img alt="An example :class:`Gtk.Expander`" src="expander.png">
    </picture>

    This is similar to the triangles used in a :class:`Gtk.TreeView`.

    Normally you use an expander as you would use a frame; you create
    the child widget and use :meth:`Gtk.Expander.set_child` to add it
    to the expander. When the expander is toggled, it will take care of
    showing and hiding the child automatically.

    # Special Usage

    There are situations in which you may prefer to show and hide the
    expanded widget yourself, such as when you want to actually create
    the widget at expansion time. In this case, create a :class:`Gtk.Expander`
    but do not add a child to it. The expander widget has an
    :attr:`Gtk.Expander.expanded` property which can be used to
    monitor its expansion state. You should watch this property with
    a signal connection as follows:

    .. code-block:: c

        static void
        expander_callback (GObject    *object,
                           GParamSpec *param_spec,
                           gpointer    user_data)
        {
          :class:`Gtk.Expander` *expander;

          expander = GTK_EXPANDER (object);

          if (:meth:`Gtk.Expander.get_expanded` (expander))
            {
              // Show or create widgets
            }
          else
            {
              // Hide or destroy widgets
            }
        }

        static void
        create_expander (void)
        {
          :class:`Gtk.Widget` *expander = :meth:`Gtk.Expander.new_with_mnemonic` ("_More Options");
