    inside a :class:`Gtk.Dialog`. It exposes the :class:`Gtk.FileChooser`
    interface, so you can use all of the :class:`Gtk.FileChooser` functions
    on the file chooser dialog as well as those for :class:`Gtk.Dialog`.

    Note that :class:`Gtk.FileChooserDialog` does not have any methods of its
    own. Instead, you should use the functions that work on a
    :class:`Gtk.FileChooser`.

    If you want to integrate well with the platform you should use the
    :class:`Gtk.FileChooserNative` API, which will use a platform-specific
    dialog if available and fall back to :class:`Gtk.FileChooserDialog`
    otherwise.

    ## Typical usage

    In the simplest of cases, you can the following code to use
    :class:`Gtk.FileChooserDialog` to select a file for opening:

    .. code-block:: c

        static void
        on_open_response (:class:`Gtk.Dialog` *dialog,
                          int        response)
        {
          if (response == GTK_RESPONSE_ACCEPT)
            {
              :class:`Gtk.FileChooser` *chooser = GTK_FILE_CHOOSER (dialog);

              g_autoptr(GFile) file = :meth:`Gtk.FileChooser.get_file` (chooser);

              open_file (file);
            }

          :meth:`Gtk.Window.destroy` (GTK_WINDOW (dialog));
        }

          // ...
          :class:`Gtk.Widget` *dialog;
          :class:`Gtk.FileChooserAction` action = GTK_FILE_CHOOSER_ACTION_OPEN;

          dialog = gtk_file_chooser_dialog_new ("Open File",
                                                parent_window,
                                                action,
                                                _("_Cancel"),
                                                GTK_RESPONSE_CANCEL,
                                                _("_Open"),
                                                GTK_RESPONSE_ACCEPT,
                                                NULL);

          :meth:`Gtk.Window.present` (GTK_WINDOW (dialog));

          g_signal_connect (dialog, "response",
                            G_CALLBACK (on_open_response),
                            NULL);

