        It may be different from the :class:`Gtk.PrintDialog`'s page setup
        if the user changed it during the setup process.
        """
    def get_print_settings(self) -> PrintSettings:
        """
        Returns the print settings of ``setup``.

        They may be different from the :class:`Gtk.PrintDialog`'s settings
        if the user changed them during the setup process.
        """
    def ref(self) -> PrintSetup:
        """
        Increase the reference count of ``setup``.
        """
    def unref(self) -> None:
        """
        Decrease the reference count of ``setup``.

        If the reference count reaches zero,
        the object is freed.
        """

class PrintUnixDialog(Dialog, Accessible, Buildable, ConstraintTarget, Native, Root, ShortcutManager):
    """
    A print dialog for platforms which don’t provide a native
    print dialog, like Unix.

    <picture>
      <source srcset="printdialog-dark.png" media="(prefers-color-scheme: dark)">
      <img alt="An example :class:`Gtk.PrintUnixDialog`" src="printdialog.png">
    </picture>

    It can be used very much like any other GTK dialog, at the cost of
    the portability offered by the high-level printing API with
    :class:`Gtk.PrintOperation`.

    In order to print something with :class:`Gtk.PrintUnixDialog`, you need to
    use :meth:`Gtk.PrintUnixDialog.get_selected_printer` to obtain a
    :class:`Gtk.Printer` object and use it to construct a :class:`Gtk.PrintJob`
    using :meth:`Gtk.PrintJob.new`.

    :class:`Gtk.PrintUnixDialog` uses the following response values:

    - :data:`Gtk.ResponseType.OK`: for the “Print” button
    - :data:`Gtk.ResponseType.APPLY`: for the “Preview” button
    - :data:`Gtk.ResponseType.CANCEL`: for the “Cancel” button

    # :class:`Gtk.PrintUnixDialog` as :class:`Gtk.Buildable`

    The :class:`Gtk.PrintUnixDialog` implementation of the :class:`Gtk.Buildable` interface
    exposes its ``notebook`` internal children with the name “notebook”.

    An example of a :class:`Gtk.PrintUnixDialog` UI definition fragment:

    .. code-block:: xml

        <object class=":class:`Gtk.PrintUnixDialog`" id="dialog1">
          <child internal-child="notebook">
            <object class=":class:`Gtk.Notebook`" id="notebook">
              <child>
                <object type=":class:`Gtk.NotebookPage`">
                  <property name="tab_expand">False</property>
                  <property name="tab_fill">False</property>
                  <property name="tab">
                    <object class=":class:`Gtk.Label`" id="tablabel">
                      <property name="label">Tab label</property>
                    </object>
                  </property>
                  <property name="child">
                    <object class=":class:`Gtk.Label`" id="tabcontent">
                      <property name="label">Content on notebook tab</property>
                    </object>
                  </property>
                </object>
              </child>
            </object>
          </child>
        </object>

