class ScrolledWindow(Widget, Accessible, Buildable, ConstraintTarget):
    """
    Makes its child scrollable.

    <picture>
      <source srcset="scrolledwindow-dark.png" media="(prefers-color-scheme: dark)">
      <img alt="An example :class:`Gtk.ScrolledWindow`" src="scrolledwindow.png">
    </picture>

    It does so using either internally added scrollbars or externally
    associated adjustments, and optionally draws a frame around the child.

    Widgets with native scrolling support, i.e. those whose classes implement
    the :class:`Gtk.Scrollable` interface, are added directly. For other types
    of widget, the class :class:`Gtk.Viewport` acts as an adaptor, giving
    scrollability to other widgets. :meth:`Gtk.ScrolledWindow.set_child`
    intelligently accounts for whether or not the added child is a :class:`Gtk.Scrollable`.
    If it isn’t, then it wraps the child in a :class:`Gtk.Viewport`. Therefore, you can
    just add any child widget and not worry about the details.

    If :meth:`Gtk.ScrolledWindow.set_child` has added a :class:`Gtk.Viewport` for you,
    it will be automatically removed when you unset the child.
    Unless :attr:`Gtk.ScrolledWindow.hscrollbar-policy` and
    :attr:`Gtk.ScrolledWindow.vscrollbar-policy` are :data:`Gtk.PolicyType.NEVER` or
    :data:`Gtk.PolicyType.EXTERNAL`, :class:`Gtk.ScrolledWindow` adds internal :class:`Gtk.Scrollbar` widgets
    around its child. The scroll position of the child, and if applicable the
    scrollbars, is controlled by the :attr:`Gtk.ScrolledWindow.hadjustment`
    and :attr:`Gtk.ScrolledWindow.vadjustment` that are associated with the
    :class:`Gtk.ScrolledWindow`. See the docs on :class:`Gtk.Scrollbar` for the details,
    but note that the “step_increment” and “page_increment” fields are only
    effective if the policy causes scrollbars to be present.

    If a :class:`Gtk.ScrolledWindow` doesn’t behave quite as you would like, or
    doesn’t have exactly the right layout, it’s very possible to set up
    your own scrolling with :class:`Gtk.Scrollbar` and for example a :class:`Gtk.Grid`.

    # Touch support

    :class:`Gtk.ScrolledWindow` has built-in support for touch devices. When a
    touchscreen is used, swiping will move the scrolled window, and will
    expose 'kinetic' behavior. This can be turned off with the
    :attr:`Gtk.ScrolledWindow.kinetic-scrolling` property if it is undesired.

    :class:`Gtk.ScrolledWindow` also displays visual 'overshoot' indication when
    the content is pulled beyond the end, and this situation can be
    captured with the ``Gtk.ScrolledWindow::edge-overshot`` signal.

    If no mouse device is present, the scrollbars will overlaid as
    narrow, auto-hiding indicators over the content. If traditional
    scrollbars are desired although no mouse is present, this behaviour
    can be turned off with the :attr:`Gtk.ScrolledWindow.overlay-scrolling`
    property.

    # Shortcuts and Gestures

    The following signals have default keybindings:

    - ``Gtk.ScrolledWindow::scroll-child``

    # CSS nodes

    :class:`Gtk.ScrolledWindow` has a main CSS node with name scrolledwindow.
    It gets a .frame style class added when :attr:`Gtk.ScrolledWindow.has-frame`
    is ``True``.

    It uses subnodes with names overshoot and undershoot to draw the overflow
    and underflow indications. These nodes get the .left, .right, .top or .bottom
    style class added depending on where the indication is drawn.

    :class:`Gtk.ScrolledWindow` also sets the positional style classes (.left, .right,
    .top, .bottom) and style classes related to overlay scrolling
    (.overlay-indicator, .dragging, .hovering) on its scrollbars.

    If both scrollbars are visible, the area where they meet is drawn
    with a subnode named junction.

    # Accessibility

    Until GTK 4.10, :class:`Gtk.ScrolledWindow` used the :class:`Gtk.AccessibleRole.group` role.

    Starting from GTK 4.12, :class:`Gtk.ScrolledWindow` uses the :class:`Gtk.AccessibleRole.generic`
    role.
    """
    gimeta: ClassVar[_GIMeta]
    child: Widget
    hadjustment: Adjustment
    has_frame: bool
    hscrollbar_policy: PolicyType | int
    kinetic_scrolling: bool
    max_content_height: int
    max_content_width: int
    min_content_height: int
    min_content_width: int
    overlay_scrolling: bool
    propagate_natural_height: bool
    propagate_natural_width: bool
    vadjustment: Adjustment
