    following sample code we create two :class:`Gtk.TreeView` widgets each with a
    view of the same data.  As the model is wrapped here by a
    :class:`Gtk.TreeModelSort`, the two :class:`Gtk.TreeView`s can each sort their
    view of the data without affecting the other.  By contrast, if we
    simply put the same model in each widget, then sorting the first would
    sort the second.

    ## Using a :class:`Gtk.TreeModelSort`

    .. code-block:: c

        {
          :class:`Gtk.TreeView` *tree_view1;
          :class:`Gtk.TreeView` *tree_view2;
          :class:`Gtk.TreeModel` *sort_model1;
          :class:`Gtk.TreeModel` *sort_model2;
          :class:`Gtk.TreeModel` *child_model;

          // get the child model
          child_model = get_my_model ();

          // Create the first tree
          sort_model1 = :meth:`Gtk.TreeModelSort.new_with_model` (child_model);
          tree_view1 = :meth:`Gtk.TreeView.new_with_model` (sort_model1);

          // Create the second tree
          sort_model2 = :meth:`Gtk.TreeModelSort.new_with_model` (child_model);
          tree_view2 = :meth:`Gtk.TreeView.new_with_model` (sort_model2);

          // Now we can sort the two models independently
          :meth:`Gtk.TreeSortable.set_sort_column_id` (GTK_TREE_SORTABLE (sort_model1),
                                                COLUMN_1, GTK_SORT_ASCENDING);
          :meth:`Gtk.TreeSortable.set_sort_column_id` (GTK_TREE_SORTABLE (sort_model2),
                                                COLUMN_1, GTK_SORT_DESCENDING);
        }

