    ## Coordinate systems in :class:`Gtk.TreeView` API

    Several different coordinate systems are exposed in the :class:`Gtk.TreeView` API.
    These are:

    ![](tree-view-coordinates.png)

    - Widget coordinates: Coordinates relative to the widget (usually ``widget->window``).

    - Bin window coordinates: Coordinates relative to the window that :class:`Gtk.TreeView` renders to.

    - Tree coordinates: Coordinates relative to the entire scrollable area of :class:`Gtk.TreeView`. These
      coordinates start at (0, 0) for row 0 of the tree.

    Several functions are available for converting between the different
    coordinate systems.  The most common translations are between widget and bin
    window coordinates and between bin window and tree coordinates. For the
    former you can use :meth:`Gtk.TreeView.convert_widget_to_bin_window_coords`
    (and vice versa), for the latter :meth:`Gtk.TreeView.convert_bin_window_to_tree_coords`
    (and vice versa).

    ## :class:`Gtk.TreeView` as :class:`Gtk.Buildable`

    The :class:`Gtk.TreeView` implementation of the :class:`Gtk.Buildable` interface accepts
    :class:`Gtk.TreeViewColumn` objects as ``<child>`` elements and exposes the
    internal :class:`Gtk.TreeSelection` in UI definitions.

    An example of a UI definition fragment with :class:`Gtk.TreeView`:

    .. code-block:: xml

        <object class=":class:`Gtk.TreeView`" id="treeview">
          <property name="model">liststore1</property>
          <child>
            <object class=":class:`Gtk.TreeViewColumn`" id="test-column">
              <property name="title">Test</property>
              <child>
                <object class=":class:`Gtk.CellRendererText`" id="test-renderer"/>
                <attributes>
                  <attribute name="text">1</attribute>
                </attributes>
              </child>
            </object>
          </child>
          <child internal-child="selection">
            <object class=":class:`Gtk.TreeSelection`" id="selection">
              <signal name="changed" handler="on_treeview_selection_changed"/>
            </object>
          </child>
        </object>

    ## CSS nodes

    .. code-block:: text

        treeview.view
        ├── header
        │   ├── button
        │   │   ╰── [sort-indicator]
        ┊   ┊
        │   ╰── button
        │       ╰── [sort-indicator]
        │
        ├── [rubberband]
        ╰── [dndtarget]

